entries.title: Rare sea monster washes up on island
entries.contentSnippet: THE remains of a mysterious serpent-like oarfish that once lived at the bottom of the ocean have washed up on a popular island
entries.content: THE remains of a mysterious serpent-like oarfish that once lived at the bottom of the ocean have washed up on a popular island

entries.title: Time is ticking for Australia’s first nuclear waste dump
entries.contentSnippet: WHEN you hear the words ‘nuclear facility’, Chernobyl and Fukushima spring to mind.
entries.content: So it’s no wonder many Aussies baulk at the thought of producing this radioactive material, let alone storing it in our backyard.

entries.title: Businessman builds Star Trek office
entries.contentSnippet: THE USS Enterprise from Star Trek is now a reality following the six-year construction of a building in China.
entries.content: Reported by Mashable, the building is the main office of Netdragon Websoft, a Chinese gaming and mobile internet company, and cost an astonishing $A204 million ($US160 million) to construct.

entries.title: Taking an Uber is about to get more expensive
entries.contentSnippet: CONTROVERSIAL ride-sharing app Uber is considering legal action to challenge a tax office ruling that requires its drivers to pay GST in line with taxi operators.
entries.content: Reported by Mashable, the building is the main office of Netdragon Websoft, a Chinese gaming and mobile internet company, and cost an astonishing $A204 million ($US160 million) to construct.

entries.title: Third time lucky with compact M3
entries.contentSnippet: Canon improves but doesn’t perfect its third-generation compact system camera, the EOS M3
entries.content: CANON’S efforts to embrace the compact system camera market are easily summed up: if at first you don’t succeed, try and try again.

entries.title: TPG makes $1.4b play for iiNet
entries.contentSnippet: INTERNET provider TPG Telecom is set to take over rival iiNet in a deal worth $1.4 billion.
entries.content: iiNet’s board of directors has recommended shareholders accept the $8.60 per share offer, which is 33 per cent above the company’s five-day average stock price.The board views this as a significant reward for shareholders who have shown their faith in iiNet, iiNet chairman Michael Smith said.

entries.title: Why it’s not the right time for the Apple Watch
entries.contentSnippet: APPLE released the much-anticipated — and much-hyped — Apple Watch last week, with CEO Tim Cook putting its best face forward.
entries.content: Unfortunately for Cook, he never gave us a reason to want or need the gee-whiz gadgetry. When Steve Jobs debuted the iPod, it too was not the first to turn MP3 music into gold — but he made you want that device..

entries.title: Chinese tech giant Huawei wants Aussie students
entries.contentSnippet: CHINESE technology company Huawei is on the hunt for Australian talent. Huawei has teamed up with the Australian Technology Network of Universities (ATN) for a three-year partnership that will see 30 Australian students embark on a Chinese adventure.
entries.content: The move is another sign that the company is serious about global engagement as it seeks to increase brand awareness in overseas markets.

entries.title: Twitter shares dive following earnings leak
entries.contentSnippet: TWITTER shares plunged Tuesday after an earnings report fell short of market expectations, despite a jump in the number of active monthly users above 300 million.
entries.content: Revenue during the first three months of this year was $US436 million ($A545 million), Twitter said, but the San Francisco company had been expected to bring in about $US456 million ($A570 million).

entries.title: 250,000 Tinder prowlers paid for right to unswipe
entries.contentSnippet: UNDOING a swipe on Tinder is a privilege worth paying for.
entries.content: That’s what more than 250,000 prowlers across the global dating scene have already decided since the red-hot hook-up app launched a paid version of its service last month, according to numbers released this week.
